solutions.content:
Hello, while it may seem like a difficult one, the fourth question can be done with an almost bruteforce approach with some optimizations.

Let dp[i][j] denote the maximum number of ones we can cover with i carpets till index j(**with current carpet ending exactly at index j**). Assuming that the current carpet ends at exactly j *greatly simplifies* the problem

Now, dp[i][j]= number of ones in string[j:j-len]+ max(dp[i-1][j-len], dp[i-1][j-len-1],....dp[i-1][0])

Optimizations:
We store this max part of previous iteration of i till j-len in a helper variable. (prevmax)
We use prefix sum array to calculate number of white blocks in a range in O(1) time
We only need the ith and i-1th rows of the dp array, so space can be reduced (didn't do it due to time constraints during contest)

```
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumWhiteTiles(string floor, int numCarpets, int carpetLen) {
        int dp[1001][1001]={0};
        int pre[1000]={0};
        if(floor[0]=='1')pre[0]=1;
        for(int i=1;i<floor.size();i++){
            pre[i]+=pre[i-1];
            if(floor[i]=='1')pre[i]++;
        }
        for(int i=1;i<=numCarpets;i++){
            int prevmax=0;
            for(int j=0;j<floor.size();j++){
                if(j<carpetLen) dp[i][j]=pre[j];
                else{
                    prevmax=max(prevmax,dp[i-1][j-carpetLen]);
                    dp[i][j]=pre[j]-pre[j-carpetLen]+prevmax;
                }
            }
        }
        int ans=0;
        for(int i=0;i<floor.size();i++)ans=max(ans,dp[numCarpets][i]);
        return pre[floor.size()-1]-ans;
    }
};
```

