solutions.content:
We can solve this problem by using standard concepts of solving a 2-d DP problem.
For each tile, we have two options --
i) We place a the carpet starting from the current tile
ii) We do not place a carpet

Further, here is an observations to be made
-- Placing carpet starting from a black tile is not feasible. SO before placing a carpet, we will check whether the current tile is white or not.


Below is the code for the approach explained above. Lines have been commented in order to understand better.

```
int solve(string &a,int i,int j,int k,int len,vector<vector<long long int>> &dp)
{

    // dp states --
    //     i --> represents the index of the tiles
    //     j --> represents the number of black carpets used

    if(i>=a.size())
    {
        // base case
        return 0;
    }

    if(dp[i][j]!=-1)
    {
        // since the current tile is already black, no need of covering it

        return dp[i][j];
    }


    if(a[i]=='1')
    {
        // the current tile is white in color, so we have two options

        int op1=INT_MAX,op2=INT_MAX;

        // option 1 - place carpet

        if(j<k) // we can only place carpets if we have some remaining black carpets
            op1=solve(a,i+len,j+1,k,len,dp);

        // option 2 - dont place the carpet
        op2=1+solve(a,i+1,j,k,len,dp);


        return dp[i][j]=min(op1,op2);
    }

    return dp[i][j]=solve(a,i+1,j,k,len,dp);

}

class Solution {
public:
    int minimumWhiteTiles(string a, int k, int len) {

        // creating a two dimensional dp array
        vector<vector<long long int>> dp(a.size()+10,vector<long long int>(k+10,-1));

        return solve(a,0,0,k,len,dp);

    }
};

```

