# Approach
Three choices
1. Use carpet if available and necessary. In this can case jump to index + carpet length
2. Do not use carpet even if available and necessary. Increase count by 1 and move to next index. Here we save carpt to be used later. 
3. Handle scenarios like no carpet available or carpet not necessary because tile is lready black. 


# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(floorLength * numberOfCarpets)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(floorLength * numberOfCarpets)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int minimumWhiteTiles(String floor, int numCarpets, int carpetLen) {
        int[][] memo = new int[floor.length()][numCarpets+1];
        for(int[] arr : memo) {
            Arrays.fill(arr, -1);
        }
        return solve(floor, numCarpets, carpetLen, 0, memo);
    }

    int solve(String floor, int numCarpets, int carpetLen, int index, int[][] memo) {
        if(index >= floor.length()) {
            return 0;
        }
        if(memo[index][numCarpets] != -1) {
            return memo[index][numCarpets];
        }
        if(numCarpets > 0) {
            if(floor.charAt(index) == '0') {
                return memo[index][numCarpets] = solve(floor, numCarpets, carpetLen, index+1, memo);
            }
            else {
                int coveredWhite = solve(floor, numCarpets-1, carpetLen, index+carpetLen, memo);
                int unCoveredWhite = 1 + solve(floor, numCarpets, carpetLen, index+1, memo);
                return memo[index][numCarpets] = Math.min(coveredWhite, unCoveredWhite);
            }
        }
        else {
            int count = 0;
            for(int i = index; i < floor.length(); i++) {
                count = floor.charAt(i) == '1' ? count + 1 : count;
            }
            return memo[index][numCarpets] = count;
        }
    }
}
```

